The opening matla of chapter 115 — **"Koi ummeed bar nahin aati / Koi soorat nazar nahin aati"** — is the most famous couplet for hopelessness. It is the title verse of the entire ghazal, and its first line literally translates as "No hope comes to fruition." The radif ("nahin aati" — does not come) repeats through all 10 couplets, but this opening verse is the poem's defining statement of despair.
